  "runtimeMin": 91,
  "format": "A movie swap with a soft espionage thread: Amanda's pick, Bobby's, and the classic Bobby had never seen. They work through all three in release order.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "'Casablanca' — Bobby finally watches",
      "note": "Amanda's pick for Bobby; the Ur Hollywood movie",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Casablanca",
          "year": 1942,
          "note": "Bobby's first watch after years of being needled about it. A tight 100 minutes that still doesn't drag: Bogart and Bergman, Claude Rains as Renault, a mostly international cast of real European exiles, and a Max Steiner score built around 'As Time Goes By' after he couldn't get it cut. Won Best Picture, Director (Michael Curtiz), and Screenplay; came in tied at No. 63 on the 2022 Sight and Sound poll."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "'The In-Laws' — Amanda's pick",
      "note": "Falk and Arkin, 1979",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The In-Laws",
          "year": 1979,
          "note": "Arthur Hiller's comedy, written by Andrew Bergman, recently added to the Criterion Collection. A Long Island dentist (Alan Arkin) meets his daughter's future father-in-law (Peter Falk), a supposed CIA operative, and gets dragged into a spy caper. The 'serpentine!' tarmac run and the firing-squad scene are the standouts; Ed Begley Jr., James Hong, and David Paymer fill out the cast."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "'Spy Kids' — Bobby's pick",
      "note": "Robert Rodriguez, 2001",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Spy Kids",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "The first movie Bobby remembers seeing in theaters. Rodriguez wrote, directed, shot, and scored it: a $35M film that made nearly $150M, with Antonio Banderas and Carla Gugino as retired-spy parents and Alexa Vega and Daryl Sabara as the kids who rescue them. Alan Cumming and Tony Shalhoub play the villains, plus Danny Trejo (the seed of Machete), Cheech Marin, and a George Clooney cameo. Sean calls it 'Oppenheimer for kids.'"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
